More Quantum Gates

20.5 Œºs

As you might have thought, there do exist gates, other than the previously defined ones.

23.6 Œºs

Single qubit gates

31.9 Œºs

The RùúëZ gate

54.9 Œºs

Passing a qubit through the RùúëZ is equivalent to multiplying its state vector by [100eùúëi]. Remember, eiŒ∏=cos(ùúÉ)+isin(ùúÉ).

The RùúëZ gate can be alternatively denoted by, [e‚àíùúëi/200eùúëi/2]. Its just the original matrix, multiplied by e‚àíùúëi/2. We can do this since multiplication by e‚àíùúëi/2 is not observable during measurement as its a complex unit and |eiŒ∏|=|cos(ùúÉ)+isin(ùúÉ)|=1. Remember that the abstract value of a complex number a+ib, i.e., |a+ib|=a2+b2 and sin2Œ∏+cos2Œ∏=1.

Considering a qubit, a|0‚å™+b|0‚å™, passing it through the Rùûπ2Z gate is equivalent to [100eùúãi/2] . And since cos(ùûπ2)=0 and sin(ùûπ2)=1, we can rewrite the above as, [100i] [ab].

31.8 Œºs

Lets try the above in Yao! The RùúëZ gate can be used in Yao with the shift block.

The T Gate

29.6 Œºs

The T gate is equivalent to Rùûπ4Z. In its matrix form, it can be written as [1001+i2]. Nevertheless, in Yao, it can be used by using the T block .

The RùúëX gate

42.5 Œºs

Similar to the RùúëZ gate, the RùúëX gate can be represented by [cos(ùúë2)‚àísin(ùúë2)i‚àísin(ùúë2)icos(ùúë2)].

19.5 Œºs

The RùúëY gate

19.2 Œºs

The Measure Gate

62.6 Œºs

We already know how to measure the qubits. We can do it in the circuit itself too.

16.3 Œºs
xxxxxxxxxx
4
 
1
begin
2
    MeasureGate = chain(2, repeat(H, 1:2), Measure(2, locs=1:2))
3
    plot(MeasureGate)
4
end

The LabeledBlock

23.5 Œºs

1

2

5
    plot(circuit)
6
end

Whats the difference between the DaggeredBlock and adjoint ' ?

One is a function of Yao, while another of Base julia. Both perform the same operation on their input, but DaggeredBlock is many times faster.
